Prediction of Future House Value

Report by Carlos Neves

for the Amazon Development Center Scotland’s position of Machine learning Scientist - Talent Sourcing.

Introduction

Question:

This exercise aims at predicting the value a given house will sell for, using the UK governments’s land registry data for the the years 1995-2015. For more information about the variables available for this dataset, refer to the descriptions.

Approach:

The value at which a house will sell is represented by a continuous variable. In the absence of clear classes in the data, regression methods are more appropriate for this analysis. As such, linear regression, a simple but efficient regression algorithm, was used as an initial approach for the prediction of house prices considering different factors.

Set up environment for analysis

Initially all the required packages for the analysis were loaded. These include:

  • data.table: A package to efficiently load and manage large data files
  • doParallel: A package that allows to set the number of cores used for parallelized analysis
  • caret: A package for Classification And REgression Training, which aims to provide a uniform interface for various machine learning functions
  • gridExtra: A package that allows to automatically arrange multiple plots
  • dplyr: A package for easy data manipulation
# Load required packages
library('data.table')
library('doParallel')
library('caret')
library('gridExtra')
library('dplyr')

# Set number of cores to maximum
registerDoParallel(detectCores())

Number of cores available: 24

Due to the use of randomization during the analysis, a random seed was defined, so the analysis can be consistently reproduced.

# Select random seed
seed <- sample(1:1000, size = 1)
set.seed(seed)

Seed used for this report: 91

After the required packages/libraries are loaded, the data is read into R using the fread function. The variables of interest for this analysis are selected while the data is loaded. These variables are:

  • Price (V2): Sale price stated on the transfer deed.
  • Date of Transfer (V3): Date when the sale was completed, as stated on the transfer deed
  • Property Type (V5): D = Detached, S = Semi-Detached, T = Terraced, F = Flats/Maisonettes, O = Other
  • Lease duration (V7): Relates to the tenure: F = Freehold, L= Leasehold etc.
  • Town/City (V12): Location of the property
# Create a vector with the number of the relevant variables
cols_interest <- c(2, 3, 5, 7, 12)

Data pre-processing

Looking at the first entries of the data, it is clear that the Date of Transfer (V3) is excessively descriptive for the purpose of this analysis, as only the year of transfer is of interest. Also the Town/City (V12) contains too many possible values. As such these variables were simplified by maintaining only the year of the Date of Transfer and a logic vector of whether or not the property is in London.

# Check for all the possible variants of LONDON's location
unique(grep(pattern = 'LONDON', data$V12, value = TRUE))
## [1] "LONDON"

# Add the new simplified variables
data <- data %>% 
        mutate('Date' = gsub(pattern = '-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{2} [0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2}', replacement = '', data$V3)) %>% 
        mutate('London' = data$V12 =='LONDON')

Exploratory data analysis

With all the data processed and split appropriately, the distribution of the house prices and how these relate to the predictor (categorical) variables was explored.

This analysis will focus on three variables:

  • Lease duration
  • Property type
  • Location (inside or outside of London)
# Take a subset sample of the data to speed the exploratory analysis
idx_sample <- sample(nrow(train), size = 10000)
hist(train$Price[idx_sample], xlab = 'Property price / £', main = 'Distribution of house prices')

The distribution of prices is highly skewed. As this could interfere with the regression analysis, the house prices were log transformed to correct for the observed skewness.

hist(log(train$Price[idx_sample]), xlab = 'ln(Property price)/ £', main = 'Distribution of log-transformed house prices')

The price distribution is now much more regular (normally distributed).

All the predictive variables seem to have some influence on the property price. From the plots, the property type and its location (in or out of London) seem to have more varied prices than the lease type.

Model building

A baseline model was built in order to understand if the trained regression models are in fact useful. The baseline model will assume that the prediction made for the price of the house is the most likely value. As such, it will simply predict the median price of all the houses, regardless of the house specifications. Two linear regressions, either considering Lease type or not, were trained to predict the house price. To increase the accuracy of these two models, k-fold cross-validation (k = 10) was used during the model training.

# Base model
model_base <- median(log(train$Price))

# Linear regression model
model_lr1 <- train(log(Price) ~ Type + London, data = train, method = 'lm', trControl = trainControl(method = 'cv', number = 10))

model_lr2 <- train(log(Price) ~ Type + London + Lease, data = train, method = 'lm', trControl = trainControl(method = 'cv', number = 10))

Model selection

Since the outcome variable is continuous and modelled using regression analysis, the root mean square error (RMSE) performance metric was used to compare models. The RMSE provides a good estimate of the total difference between the estimated and real property prices, so that the smaller the value the more accurate the predictions are expected to be. Because the model output variable was a logarithm, it needs to be exponentiated to match the prices and make he RMSE more interpretable.

#Cross-validate base model
postResample(pred = exp(rep(model_base, times = nrow(validation))), obs = validation$Price)[1]

From the regression summaries, it would seem that all the predictors considered are significant for the model. In fact, both models have a root mean square error lower than the base model, with the linear regression considering the three different predictors showing a slightly improved performance. As such, the latter model (model_lr2) was selected to predict the house values.

Model testing

The chosen model was evaluated against new data from the test set and the RMSE performance was estimated. The model residuals were additionally plotted to better understand how the model performs for different ranges of house prices.

# Model performance
predicted <- exp(predict(model_lr2, newdata = test))
postResample(pred = predicted, obs = test$Price)[1]
##     RMSE 
## 334378.1

# Residuals plot
idx_sample <- sample(length(predicted), size = 10000)
predicted_sample <- predicted[idx_sample]
residuals <-(predicted_sample - test$Price[idx_sample])/100000

ggplot(data.frame(residuals, predicted_sample), aes(x = predicted_sample, y = residuals)) + 
        geom_point(shape = 1) + 
        ggtitle('Residuals for the estimated house prices in 2015') + 
        theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) + 
        geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = 'red') + 
        ylab('Residuals /100000 £') + 
        xlab('Predicted price / £')

# Remove variables not required any more from environment
rm(model_base, model_lr1, train, validation, idx_sample, predicted_sample, residuals)

The residuals plot shows a clear y-axis unbalance (with a few large deviations). This is most likely related to the skewed distribution of prices, where most property prices are less than £400k, but a few outlying cases cost more than £800k (please refer to the first histogram), which results in a systematic under-evaluation of the property price by the model.

Predicting house values

Finally, some house prices were predicted to illustrate some of the model’s potential uses. For example, it may be relevant to consider the price difference for a similar property in London, compared to outside of London, if one is considering investing in the property market.

house1 <- c('Type' = 'D', 'Lease' = 'F', 'London' = 'out London')
house2 <- c('Type' = 'D', 'Lease' = 'F', 'London' = 'in London')
prices <- exp(predict(model_lr2, newdata = t(data.frame(house1, house2))))

A detached house with freehold lease in London is predicted to sell for £194066, while a similar house outside London would sell for £194066. That’s a difference of £254497!

Conclusions

The model trained in this exercise is an initial attempt to predict house prices. This exercise illustrated the various steps from raw data to predictions, including data pre-processing, exploratory analysis, cross-validation, model selection and model evaluation. In this particular case, the final model is biased to negative residuals (under-valuation) when tested with new data. This could potentially be solved by including additional variables to the model, particularly the date of transaction, since all predictions were of ‘future’ prices (in respect to the training data). The effect of the year of sale is illustrated below:

p_date

# Remove variables not required any more from environment
rm(house1, house2, prices, model_lr2, p_date, predicted, test)
